---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

/*
  Dated research note — frozen to the 2026-07-17 daily print (methodology
  v2.2.0). Research notes are dated, not updated in place; the living
  surfaces are /rates, /term, /basis, /credit, /realized. All numbers are
  hardcoded from the 2026-07-17 rates_daily + committed_mi publication —
  this page must not import the live datasets.
*/
const AS_OF = '2026-07-17';
---
<Base
  title="The Basis Layer, Measured: What a GPU-Hour's Price Depends On · CCIR Research"
  description="A GPU-hour is not one price. On one day's print the same H100-hour posts at $9.15, $3.63, and $2.89 by operator segment; −25% by region; −2% to −56% by commitment term. The five basis components, measured — and the ones with no public price yet."
  ogImage="/og/basis-layer-measured.png"
  article={{ published: '2026-07-17' }}
>
  <section class="wrap top">
    <header class="page-head">
      <div class="kicker">Research · {AS_OF} · window: the 2026-07-17 daily print, methodology v2.2.0</div>
      <h1>The Basis Layer, Measured: What a GPU-Hour's Price Depends On</h1>
      <p class="standfirst">
        &ldquo;GPU-hour&rdquo; reads like a standardized unit. On any day's
        print it is the beginning of a description: the same-name chip, the
        same day, posts at prices that differ by multiples depending on who
        operates it, where it sits, and what the buyer can rely on. Those
        differences — not the visible ones between chips or tenors — are the
        basis layer: spreads between nominally identical units, against
        whatever reference a contract, covenant, or collateral mark chooses.
        This note freezes one day's cross-section of the spreads we measure
        daily, separates them from the axes often mistaken for basis, and
        names the components that today have no public price at all.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="sec">
      <h2><span class="n">01</span> The Same-Name Chip, Four Different Prices</h2>
      <p>
        Basis, properly used, is a spread between nominally identical units —
        the same good, delivered differently. Every figure below is from the
        July 17, 2026 daily publication: posted, publicly accessible rates
        from the fixed provider panel, guaranteed on-demand unless stated,
        panel depth (n = contributing providers) disclosed per cell; thin
        cells are labeled.
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table class="basis-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Basis component</th><th>Measured as</th><th>2026-07-17 print</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Configuration &amp; operator class</td>
              <td>Operator-segment axis, same chip (H100, guaranteed on-demand, US) · <a href="/explorer?chip=H100&interrupt=GTD&region=US">open this cut</a></td>
              <td>Hyperscaler $9.15 (n=4) · Neocloud $3.63 (n=12) · Marketplace $2.89 (n=8) — <strong>3.2&times; on the same-name chip, same region, same term</strong>. The bundle differs — fabric, ops plane, support — and the segment spread is where that difference prices</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Location</td>
              <td>Region axis, same chip and segment (Neocloud, guaranteed on-demand) · <a href="/explorer?chip=H100&tier=T2&interrupt=GTD">open this cut</a></td>
              <td>EU posts below US: H100 −25% ($2.74 vs $3.63) · H200 −12% ($3.78 vs $4.29) · B200 −21% ($6.06 vs $7.65) — identical products, persistent regional discount</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Interruptibility</td>
              <td>Guaranteed vs interruptible, same chip (H100, US) · <a href="/explorer?chip=H100&interrupt=INT">open this cut</a></td>
              <td>Hyperscaler −66% ($3.09 vs $9.15; n=2, thin) · Marketplace −19% ($2.34 vs $2.89; n=3, thin) — the price of the delivery right alone, on otherwise identical capacity</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Counterparty</td>
              <td>No posted price — observed in credit documents instead</td>
              <td>Filed spreads at signing on GPU-collateralized facilities run +2.25 to +9.62 over SOFR by contract support; unaffiliated holders of one facility file marks from 99.0 to 103.1</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        Two properties of this table matter more than any single number.
        First, these spreads are not noise around a true price — they are
        persistent, they have signs that survive day to day, and the largest
        of them exceeds the level moves the market debates. Second, each row
        is a published daily series, not a one-off study: every cell above —
        and every grain this note does not show — is browsable on the
        <a href="/explorer">series explorer</a>, and the cross-section can be
        recomputed for any publication date from the archived record.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="sec">
      <h2><span class="n">02</span> Two Axes Often Mistaken for Basis</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>The chip axis is relative value, not basis.</strong> Within
        one segment on the same day, H100 posts $3.63 (n=12), H200 $4.29
        (n=7), B200 $7.65 (n=4) — a 2.1&times; span. But an H100-hour and a
        B200-hour are different goods, the way crude and natural gas are
        different goods: the spread between them is a relative-value
        relationship with its own dynamics (generation turnover, workload
        migration), not a deviation from a common reference.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The term axis is the curve, not basis.</strong> Within one
        provider, committed schedules step down from on-demand: Neocloud
        H100 −2% at 1M (n=3), −10% at 1Y (n=7), −39% at 3Y (n=4);
        hyperscaler H100 3Y −56% (n=2). These are posted fixed schedules —
        the time dimension of the same product, tracked on the
        <a href="/term">committed term structure</a> monitor — not a spread
        between simultaneous units.
      </p>
      <p>
        The distinction is not pedantry. A reference contract can specify
        the chip and the tenor — those are contract terms. What it cannot
        specify away is everything in the table above: whoever holds
        physical capacity against a reference price holds the configuration,
        location, delivery-right, and counterparty spreads whether or not
        anyone prices them.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="sec">
      <h2><span class="n">03</span> What Has No Posted Price</h2>
      <p>
        The table's honesty requires its complement: components of the
        physical market that today have no public price, here or anywhere.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Facility-grain configuration.</strong> Our operator-segment
        axis carries much of the configuration difference — interconnect
        fabric and form factor are identifiable at the listing level (SXM vs
        PCIe, InfiniBand-class fabrics) — but a specific cluster's topology,
        oversubscription, and storage attachment do not post prices. The
        segment spread bounds this basis; it does not decompose it.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Power and facility terms.</strong> Posted GPU-hour rates
        bundle power, cooling, and facility cost. No provider posts the
        pass-through separately, so the power component of the location
        spread is not separable from the posted price alone.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Service terms.</strong> Uptime guarantees, support
        obligations, replacement rights, and scheduling restrictions change
        what a buyer receives at the same headline rate. These live in
        contracts and terms-of-service documents, not in posted prices.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Delivered versus posted.</strong> Every rate above is a
        posted, publicly accessible ask — by design, and disclosed
        throughout the methodology. What large committed deals sign at is
        not public; the nearest public evidence is filings-based realization,
        tracked on the <a href="/realized/">realized vs rate card</a> monitor.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Counterparty standing.</strong> The one component priced in
        credit documents rather than rate cards. The
        <a href="/credit">compute credit tracker</a> reproduces those terms
        as filed; it is a record, not a price.
      </p>
      <p>
        In commodity markets, differentials that mattered eventually acquired
        published assessments; differentials that did not stayed inside
        bilateral negotiations. Which of the unpriced components above
        crosses that line is an empirical question this record is built to
        answer.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="sec">
      <h2><span class="n">04</span> Sources &amp; Method</h2>
      <p>
        All rates are from the CCIR daily publication of July 17, 2026
        (methodology v2.2.0): publicly posted, provider-operated pricing
        pages captured from a fixed panel, one provider one vote, statistics
        and panel depth published per cell. Term spreads are within-provider
        — each provider's committed schedule against its own on-demand rate
        — never a ratio between cells of different panel composition.
        Credit figures are reproduced from SEC filings and issuer or lender
        releases as filed. Cells with n&le;2 are labeled thin and should be
        read as indicative.
      </p>
      <p class="data-note">
        Living surfaces: <a href="/rates">reference rates</a> ·
        <a href="/explorer">series explorer (every grain)</a> ·
        <a href="/term">committed term structure</a> ·
        <a href="/basis">on-demand vs clearing basis</a> ·
        <a href="/credit">compute credit tracker</a> ·
        <a href="/realized/">realized vs rate card</a>. The full daily series
        behind every row is downloadable from the
        <a href="/data/rates_daily.csv">rates CSV</a>.
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>

  <style>
    .top { padding-top: 32px; }
    .page-head { max-width: 82ch; margin-bottom: 10px; }
    .page-head h1 {
      font-family: var(--font-display);
      font-size: var(--fs-hero);
      line-height: var(--lh-display);
      font-weight: var(--weight-display);
      margin: 6px 0 14px;
      letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    }
    .sec { margin: 28px 0; max-width: 80ch; }
    .sec h2 {
      font-family: var(--font-display);
      font-size: var(--fs-xl);
      margin: 0 0 12px;
      display: flex;
      align-items: baseline;
      gap: 12px;
    }
    .sec .n { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--fs-sm); color: var(--accent); font-weight: var(--weight-strong); }
    .sec p { font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: var(--fs-md); color: var(--ink); line-height: 1.65; margin: 0 0 13px; }
    .sec strong { color: var(--accent); }
    .table-wrap { overflow-x: auto; margin: 0 0 13px; }
    .basis-table {
      border-collapse: collapse;
      font-family: var(--font-body);
      font-size: var(--fs-sm);
      line-height: 1.5;
      min-width: 640px;
    }
    .basis-table th {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: var(--fs-xs);
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: var(--tracking-eye);
      color: var(--ink-faint);
      text-align: left;
      padding: 8px 14px 8px 0;
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--ink-dim);
    }
    .basis-table td {
      padding: 10px 14px 10px 0;
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
      vertical-align: top;
      color: var(--ink);
    }
    .basis-table td:first-child {
      font-family: var(--font-display);
      font-weight: var(--weight-display);
      white-space: nowrap;
    }
    .basis-table td:nth-child(2) { color: var(--ink-dim); }
    .data-note { font-size: var(--fs-sm); color: var(--ink-dim); }
  </style>
</Base>
